data.title: Taylor Swiftâ€™s Midnights album: What do all the lyrics mean?
data.meta_description: What every song on Taylor Swiftâ€™s Midnights album is about, including â€œAnti-Hero,â€ â€œThe Great War,â€ â€œWouldâ€™ve, Couldâ€™ve, Shouldâ€™ve.â€
data.text:
As of October 21 at midnight, Taylor Swiftâ€™s 10th studio album, Midnights, is officially out in the world, and besides the obvious question (is it more like Reputation or more like Lover?), fans can finally dig into all the lyrical hints and Easter eggs characteristic of a much-hyped Swift release in their standard manner: fanatically.

Of course, there have already been fun little gems for Swifties to enjoy; for one, Midnights came out as Swift turned exactly 12,000 days old, alluding to the numbers around a clock, a present motif in her earlier work (and especially in this album). Sheâ€™s already shared that the album is made up of â€œthe stories of 13 sleepless nights scattered throughout my life,â€ and in her pre-release teasers on Instagram and TikTok, Swift revealed that â€œAnti-Heroâ€ will be the lead single, a song about her struggles with fame and biggest insecurities. â€œ[Itâ€™s] a real guided tour throughout all the things I tend to hate about myself,â€ she explains.

The rest of Midnights â€” plus its seven bonus tracks that Swift surprise-released at 3 am â€” feels equally personal; gone are the fictional stories woven throughout her pandemic indie rock albums Folklore and Evermore. Rather, Midnights is a return to an intensely autobiographical Taylor, making it extremely ripe hunting material for sleuthing Swifties. Letâ€™s get into it.

1) â€œLavender Hazeâ€

Gaylor theorists (Swifties who believe Swift is bisexual and has dated several of her female friends) may have been convinced that the â€œlavenderâ€ mentioned in the title was referring to the historically queer connotations of the color, but the first song on Midnights appears to be about Joe Alwyn, Swiftâ€™s boyfriend of six years. The singer has said as much in talking about the song on social media: â€œMy relationship for six years, weâ€™ve had to dodge weird rumors, tabloid stuff, and we just ignore it, and so this song is sort of about the act of ignoring that stuff to protect the real stuff.â€ She specified that she came across the phrase â€œlavender hazeâ€ while watching Mad Men, and that it described the feeling of being in love; Gaylors, naturally, were not pleased.

Swift and Alwyn have frequently dodged rumors and questions that theyâ€™re engaged, and this song seems to address that speculation head-on as Swift sings, â€œAll they keep asking me (all they keep asking me) is if Iâ€™m gonna be your bride. / The only girl they see (the only girl they see) is a one night or a wife.â€ This sentiment is also referenced by the line, â€œIâ€™m damned if I do give a damn what people say.â€ The lines suggest that Swift is tired of this line of questioning, and signals an interest in subverting gender roles and a desire to be seen as more than a wife or girlfriend.

2) â€œMaroonâ€

If you thought â€œLavender Hazeâ€ would be the only song on the album to reference a very specific color, youâ€™ve clearly never listened to an album by Taylor Swift, noted inventor of the color red. Everything here points to this song being about a short-lived relationship â€” possibly the one she shared with Tom Hiddleston in 2016. We know that itâ€™s referencing a failed romance (â€œHow the hell did we lose sight of us again? / Sobbinâ€™ with your head in your hands / Ainâ€™t that the way shit always ends?â€), and the pair met at the Met Gala (â€œthe one I was dancing with in New York, no shoesâ€). But one â€œMaroonâ€ mystery remains: When the hell did Swift have a roommate, not to mention one who buys â€œcheap-ass screw top rosÃ©â€?

3) â€œAnti-Heroâ€

The first single release on Midnights pits Swift against herself: The music video features Swift in a â€™70s wood-paneled den, trapped with all of her insecurities and self-loathing. In the song, Swift describes herself as the â€œproblem,â€ singing, â€œIâ€™ll stare directly at the sun / But never in the mirror / It must be exhausting rooting for the anti-hero,â€ suggesting she can endure almost anything besides coming to terms with her own problems.

â€œThis song really is a guided tour throughout all of the things I tend to hate about myself,â€ Swift previously said about it, adding, â€œI really donâ€™t think Iâ€™ve delved this far into my insecurities in his detail before.â€

Itâ€™s an honest portrayal of self-hatred, and the lyrics reveal as much as Swift pokes fun at her height while also nodding to an iconic, albeit odd reference from the television show 30 Rock: â€œSometimes I feel like everybody is a sexy baby / And Iâ€™m a monster on the hill.â€ She also says she has â€œcovert narcissism disguised as optimismâ€ and hints that she has trouble sleeping at night due to her struggles with depression and fraught relationship with food; in the music video, she steps on a scale and the number reads â€œFAT.â€

4) â€œSnow on the Beachâ€

Despite the fact that Lana Del Rey is featured on this song (barely), itâ€™s actually a happy one! â€œSnow On the Beachâ€ describes the â€œweird but fuckinâ€™ beautifulâ€ sensation of falling in love at the same time as someone is falling in love with you. Thereâ€™s also a fun callout to Janet Jacksonâ€™s iconic 2001 single â€œAll For Youâ€ (â€œNow Iâ€™m all for you like Janetâ€).

5) â€œYouâ€™re On Your Own, Kidâ€

â€œYouâ€™re On Your Own, Kidâ€ is possibly the oldest â€œmidnightâ€ out of the 13 midnights we hear described on the album: The song describes a girl waiting for a boy to notice her, but she eventually gets tired of waiting and runs away to play songs. When she finally achieves fame and fortune, however, she realizes sheâ€™s still on her own. â€œI hosted parties and starved my body / Like Iâ€™d be saved by a perfect kissâ€ recall several pieces of Swiftian lore: her very public â€œgirl squadâ€ during her 1989 era, the eating disorder she spoke about in her Netflix documentary Miss Americana, and waiting for a new love to save her. The song ends on a rather comforting note, however: You may be on your own, but you always have been, so thereâ€™s nothing to be afraid of.

6) â€œMidnight Rainâ€

Warning: The intro to â€œMidnight Rainâ€ might be a jump scare. It begins with a distorted, deep voice: â€œHe wanted it comfortable, I wanted that pain / He wanted a bride / I was making my own name / Chasing that fame, he stayed the same / All of me changed like midnight.â€ But the rest of the song is pure Taylor, alluding to the heartbreak of breaking someone elseâ€™s heart by putting oneâ€™s career ahead of a relationship.

Mentions of rain in her lyrics are famously sprinkled throughout her discography, from her self-titled debut to Evermore. It also references the themes of starting over, a woman with big dreams escaping her small-town life (see â€œâ€™Tis the damn seasonâ€ and â€œDorotheaâ€). Itâ€™s the only track with â€œmidnightâ€ in the title, suggesting that the song is both an experiment and an ode to revisiting and reinventing â€œold memories and midnights past.â€ But who is the man who stayed the same? Theorists are guessing Taylor Lautner and Hiddleston, two men sheâ€™s suspected of having dumped for being, among other things, too nice for their own good.

7) â€œQuestion ...?â€

The lyrics may literally begin with the line â€œGood girl, sad boy,â€ but Gaylors are convinced that the â€œquestionâ€ in question is directed toward Swiftâ€™s former best friend, and possible (?) kissing partner Karlie Kloss. The evidence? Frequent usage of she/her pronouns (â€œDo you wish you could still touch her?â€) and the line, â€œDid you ever have someone kiss you in a crowded room?â€ which some think is a reference to the lines in Reputationâ€™s â€œDressâ€ (which Kaylor stans believe is also about Kloss): â€œOur secret moments in your crowded room / Theyâ€™ve got no idea about you and meâ€ and â€œI donâ€™t want you like a best friend / Only bought this dress so you could take it off.â€ Theories aside, â€œQuestionâ€¦?â€ includes a classic Swiftian homage to the color of feelings: â€œBefore you painted all my nights a color Iâ€™ve searched for sinceâ€ recalls lyrics past, such as the â€œIllicit Affairsâ€ lyric â€œYou showed me colors you know I canâ€™t see with anyone elseâ€ and, well, the entirety of Red.

8) â€œVigilante Shitâ€

â€œVigilante Shitâ€ is all the evidence we need to know that â€œKarmaâ€ (Swiftâ€™s rumored album that was scrapped and reworked into Reputation in the wake of her feud with Kim Kardashian and Kanye West) is real, except this time itâ€™s also loaded with references to Scooter Braun. The heavy bass mixed with the bad-girl persona she adopted for the Reputation album cycle is on full display: â€œI donâ€™t start shit, but I can tell you how it ends / Donâ€™t get sad, get even / So on the weekends, I donâ€™t dress for friends / Lately Iâ€™ve been dressing for revenge.â€ (A Princess Diana reference? Who knows!) Itâ€™s also Swiftâ€™s second song about ruining a man to avenge a friend (following in the tradition of Evermoreâ€™s â€œNo Body, No Crime.â€ The plot here is, essentially, that an evil man cheated on his wife and did some white-collar crimes, and Swift helped the ex-wife get revenge, and both of them looked really hot. Could be about anyone, really, but weâ€™ll likely get more clues once the â€œVigilante Shitâ€ video drops, which Swifties are already convinced will happen.

9) â€œBejeweledâ€

â€œBejeweledâ€ is a song about a woman in a relationship who feels used and taken for granted by her partner, but who can still â€œmake the whole place shimmerâ€ when she walks into a room. By the end, she realizes sheâ€™s worth more than some guyâ€™s arm candy (â€œa diamondâ€™s gotta shine!â€), and for some reason, Iâ€™m personally convinced this song is about Swiftâ€™s ex-boyfriend â€œCalvinâ€ â€œHarris,â€ also referenced in the Reputation lyric, â€œIf he drops my name, then I owe him nothinâ€™ / And if he spends my change, then he had it cominâ€™.â€ I rest my case.

10) â€œLabyrinthâ€

Another Alwyn love song! This one appears to be about the anxiety Swift faces when falling in love, expecting the worst, then being pleasantly surprised that it worked out. â€œOh, Iâ€™m falling in love / I thought the plane was goinâ€™ down / Howâ€™d you turn it right around?â€ Planes are an often-used motif in Swiftâ€™s discography, seemingly symbolizing the conflicting set of emotions that come with falling in love but the fear of crashing and burning it all to the ground.

â€œLast Kissâ€ (Speak Now): â€œI do recall now the smell of rain fresh off the pavement, I ran off the pane.â€

â€œCome Backâ€¦ Be Hereâ€ (Red): â€œSpinning faster than the plane that took you.â€

â€œOut Of The Woodsâ€ (1989): â€œTwo paper airplanes flying, flying, flying, and I remember thinkingâ€¦â€

â€œGetaway Carâ€ (Reputation): â€œWe were jet set Bonnie and Clyde.â€

â€œCall It What You Wantâ€ (Reputation): â€œMy babyâ€™s fly like a jet stream high above the whole scene.â€

Swift appears to try to quash her anxieties about getting hurt from this relationship as she sings, â€œBreathe in, breathe through, breathe deep, breathe out.â€ Swift quoted this lyric in her commencement speech at New York University months before Midnights was released, saying, â€œHard things will happen to us, we will recover, we will learn from it, we will grow more resilient because of it, and as long as we are fortunate enough to be breathing, we will breathe in, breathe through, breathe deep, and breathe out.â€

11) â€œKarmaâ€

To understand the song â€œKarma,â€ you also have to understand the album Karma â€” an album that never actually existed, but that theorists believe would have been released had Kim Kardashian not â€œexposedâ€ Swift in the wake of her feud with Kanye West (read more about that here). When â€œKarmaâ€ the song was announced on the track list for Midnights, fans assumed it would be a diss track aimed at West, who has recently been under fire for antisemitic comments and racist fashion shows.

In an interview with Apple Music about Midnights, Swift explains that the song â€œis written from a perspective of feeling like, really happy, really proud of the way your life is, feeling like this must be a reward for doing stuff right and itâ€™s a song that I really love because I think we all need some of those moments. We canâ€™t just be beating ourselves up all the time.â€ The bridge also recounts and affirms Swiftâ€™s long-term planning and determination to have a lifelong career: â€œAsk me what I learned from all those years / Ask me what I earned from all those tears / Ask me why so many fade, but Iâ€™m still here.â€ Also: â€œKarma is a cat purring in my lap â€™cause it loves meâ€ might just very well be Taylor Swiftâ€™s most Taylor Swift lyric yet.

12) â€œSweet Nothingâ€

Add â€œSweet Nothingâ€ to the list of Taylor Swift songs that would be appropriate on a wedding playlist. Itâ€™s for hopeless romantics and Folklore lovers. The lyrics â€œyouâ€™re in the kitchen hummingâ€ evoke past references to the casual intimacy of being at home with a romantic partner. To name a couple, remember the dancing around the kitchen visuals in â€œAll Too Wellâ€? Or being barefoot in the kitchen with sacred new beginnings in â€œCornelia Streetâ€? Rather than the painful outcomes of the former and the anxieties rippling throughout the latter, â€œSweet Nothingâ€ portrays the comfort of Swift finally being with someone who feels like home.

What makes the song even sweeter is that itâ€™s the sixth song Swift has co-written with Alwyn. While the â€œindustry disruptors and soul deconstructors / And smooth-talking hucksters out glad-handing each otherâ€ seem to nod to Swiftâ€™s feelings of being used for her money and fame, critics of her work and personal life, and her battle to gain ownership of her masters, it is refreshing to hear lyrics suggesting Alwyn doesnâ€™t add to those stressors. â€œIâ€™m just too soft for all of it.â€ Me too, Taylor.

13) â€œMastermindâ€

This oneâ€™s definitely going to be playing in all your group fitness classes for the next six months. From lyrics on deliberation to a reminiscent bridge, â€œMastermindâ€ is a portrait of reclamation and self-analysis. The lyrics â€œwhat if I told you it was accidentalâ€ draw a parallel to Loverâ€™s â€œPaper Rings,â€ where she sings â€œI hate accidents / Except when we went from friends to this.â€ Hi again, Joe Alwyn.

Many past public criticisms have painted Swift as a master manipulator. The lyrics â€œWhat if I told you Iâ€™m the mastermind? And now youâ€™re mine / It was all by designâ€ reframe her as a clever puppet master, but her intentions are actually coming from a place of anxiety. â€œIâ€™ve been scheming like a criminal ever since to make them love me and make it seem effortlessâ€ also seems to call back to â€œIâ€™ve never been a natural / All I do is try, try, tryâ€ from â€œMirrorball.â€ Full of references to classic Swift motifs like youth and stars, this song makes clear she might very well be a mastermind.

14) â€œThe Great Warâ€

Itâ€™s not the first time Swift has referred to her relationship as a battle, but itâ€™s certainly the first time sheâ€™s compared it, literally, to World War I â€” though, like, a proper Anglophile, she uses the British term. Itâ€™s a song about the regular trials of being in a relationship: trying not to let the past creep in and sabotage what youâ€™ve built, and the relief that you can survive even the worst fights. â€œI will always be yours â€™cause we survived the Great War,â€ she sings. One can assume we know who this oneâ€™s about.

15) â€œBigger Than the Whole Skyâ€

She might be in a serious long-term relationship, but â€œBigger Than the Whole Skyâ€ is a reminder that Swift can still write a deep cut about the one that got away. Itâ€™s not clear who the song is about (some on Twitter have posited that it could be referencing a miscarriage, possibly a friendâ€™s), though anyone whoâ€™s ever had someone taken too soon can relate to the lyrics â€œGoodbye, goodbye, goodbye / You were bigger than the whole sky / You were more than just a short time.â€ No surprise that this is the biggest waterworks-inducing track on the album.

16) â€œParisâ€

Swift evokes the city of love while describing the early stages of being in a relationship, the feeling of being so infatuated that every place you go feels magical and even if youâ€™re drinking cheap wine, it tastes like champagne. Again, she says that romance is sweeter â€œif you keep it just yours,â€ and, in a possible reference to â€œMastermind,â€ she sings, â€œI want to brainwash you into loving me forever.â€ Normal!

17) â€œHigh Infidelityâ€

â€œDo you really wanna know where I was on April 29? / Do I really have to tell you how he brought me to life?â€ Swift sings on the track. This date is important because on April 29, 2016, Swiftâ€™s then-boyfriend Calvin Harris released the song â€œThis Is What You Came Forâ€ with Rihanna, a song that was later confirmed to have been written by Swift under a pseudonym, Nils Sjoberg.

At the time, Swift and Harris, who had been dating for more than a year, kept their professional collaboration under wraps. But that same day, Harris was asked in an interview whether he planned to collaborate with Swift and he responded, â€œYou know, we havenâ€™t ever spoken about it. I canâ€™t see it happening, though.â€ The couple broke up roughly a month later, and TMZ reported then that the track was the â€œbreaking pointâ€ in the pairâ€™s relationship, with Swift reportedly feeling â€œdisrespectedâ€ by Harris during the songâ€™s release.

So where was Swift on April, 29, 2016? That remains unclear, but we do know that on April 28, she was photographed celebrating BFF Gigi Hadidâ€™s birthday in Los Angeles, and images surfaced of Swift leaving the party in the early hours of April 29. Itâ€™s not known what she did the rest of the day, but by May 2, she was attending the Met Gala in New York City, which is where fans believe she met Tom Hiddleston, whom she dated after Harris.

â€œI bent the truth too far tonight / I was dancing around, dancing around it,â€ Swift sings. â€œDo you really want to know where I was on April 29? / Do I really have to tell you how he brought me back to life?â€ Fans think Swift previously sang about leaving Harris for Hiddleston on the 2017 track â€œGetaway Car.â€

18) â€œGlitchâ€

This one also appears to be inspired by Swift and Alwyn. In it, Swift sings of an unlikely relationship: â€œWe were supposed to be just friendsâ€™â€™ and â€œI thought we had no chance,â€ and seems to suggest that theyâ€™ve endured longer than she (and, perhaps, her critics) expected. â€œBut itâ€™s been two thousand one hundred ninety days of our love blackout / The systemâ€™s breaking down,â€ she sings; 2,190 days is equivalent to six years, which is roughly the amount of time that Swift and Alwyn have been together and is thought to be her longest relationship.

In the past, Swift has come under scrutiny over her romantic history, particularly for having many ex-boyfriends. In â€œGlitch,â€ Swift appears to internalize the criticism she has received as she sings â€œI was supposed to sweat you out in search of glorious happenings / of happenstance on someone elseâ€™s playground / but itâ€™s been two thousand one hundred ninety days of our love blackout.â€ The fact that her relationship has endured for this long appears to surprise Swift, who sings it â€œmust be counterfeit / I think thereâ€™s been a glitch.â€

19) â€œWouldâ€™ve, Couldâ€™ve, Shouldâ€™veâ€

Move over, Jake Gyllenhaal, the Swiftiesâ€™ new Enemy No. 1 is John Mayer, whom fans think â€œWouldâ€™ve, Couldâ€™ve, Shouldâ€™veâ€ is about. The song refers to a relationship between a 19-year-old Swift and an older man (they dated when she was 19 and he was 32, Swiftâ€™s current age). â€œNow that Iâ€™m grown, Iâ€™m scared of ghosts / Memories feel like weapons,â€ she says, acknowledging that even though â€œthe pain was heavenâ€ at the time, she regrets it ever happened.

20) â€œDear Readerâ€

â€œDear Readerâ€ is part apologia, part disclaimer: We may have been listening to Swiftâ€™s music for the past decade and a half, but here, she warns us not to trust too much of it. â€œNever take advice from someone whoâ€™s falling apart,â€ she says in the chorus, after sheâ€™s just given us a whole verse-ful of advice, then adds in the outro, â€œYou should find another guiding light, but I shine so bright.â€ Like in the rest of Midnights, Swift is reckoning with celebrity and a life thatâ€™s become too unwieldy for one person to bear. In â€œAnti-Hero,â€ she wonders whether sheâ€™s even learned anything from her fame (â€œI have this thing where I get older, but just never wiserâ€), and â€œDear Readerâ€ feels like a callback. Itâ€™s a fitting end to an extremely retrospective album, a sad but sweet reminder that Swift is, at the end of the day, human.
